$$
\begin{gathered}
\frac{1}{2 \sqrt{2}+x^{2}(y+z)}=\frac{1}{2 \sqrt{2}+x(x y+x z)}= \\
=\frac{1}{2 \sqrt{2}+x(6-y z)}=\frac{1}{6 x+2 \sqrt{2}-x y z} \leq \frac{1}{6 x}=\frac{y z}{6 x y z}
\end{gathered}
$$

Similarly for the other two terms:

$$
\frac{1}{2 \sqrt{2}+y^{2}(x+z)} \leq \frac{x z}{6 x y z}, \quad \frac{1}{2 \sqrt{2}+z^{2}(x+y)} \leq \frac{x y}{6 x y z}
$$

Adding these estimates, we get

$$
\frac{1}{2 \sqrt{2}+x^{2}(y+z)}+\frac{1}{2 \sqrt{2}+y^{2}(x+z)}+\frac{1}{2 \sqrt{2}+z^{2}(x+y)} \leq \frac{y z+x z+x y}{6 x y z}=\frac{1}{x y z}
$$

